# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: power-amplifier-rf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A **class-D amplifier**, or **switching amplifier**, is an electronic amplifier in which the amplifying devices (transistors, usually MOSFETs) operate as electronic switches, and not as linear gain devices as in other amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] They operate by rapidly switching back and forth between the supply rails, using pulse-width modulation, pulse-density modulation, or related techniques to produce a pulse train output.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A low-pass filter is typically used to attenuate their high-frequency content to provide analog output current and voltage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Little energy is dissipated in the amplifying transistors because they are always either fully on or fully off, so efficiency can exceed 90%.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Switching amplifier circuits corresponding to what is now termed class-D operation were described in the early 1930s, including an electric amplifying circuit patented by Burnice D.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Pulse-width and pulse-time modulation techniques were further developed later in the 1930s by Alec Reeves for telecommunication signaling and transmission, rather than for power amplification.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The term class-D was proposed in 1959 by P.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Baxandall in the context of transistor oscillators.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] High efficiency is obtained by arranging for the active devices to pass current only when the associated voltage is low.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In Baxandall’s circuit, this was achieved using an inductor to steer current between devices, minimizing the overlap of voltage and current during conduction.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The first commercial product was a kit module called the X-10 released by Sinclair Radionics in 1964.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] However, it had an output power of only 2.5 watts.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The Sinclair X-20 in 1966 produced 20 watts but suffered from the inconsistencies and limitations of the germanium-based bipolar junction transistors available at the time.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] As a result, these early class-D amplifiers were impractical and unsuccessful.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Practical class-D amplifiers were enabled by the development of silicon-based MOSFET (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor) technology.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In 1978, Sony introduced the TA-N88, the first class-D unit to employ power MOSFETs and a switched-mode power supply.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] There were subsequently rapid developments in MOSFET technology between 1979 and 1985.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The availability of low-cost, fast-switching MOSFETs led to class-D amplifiers becoming successful in the mid-1980s.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In 1983, Mead Killion applied for a patent describing an integrated-circuit class-D amplifier intended for use in hearing aids.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A class-D-amplifier-based integrated circuit was released by Tripath in 1996.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Phase-modulated class-D architectures have also been developed.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In these designs, a high-power switching waveform is generated on the primary side and shared across channels.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Phase displacement is generated during demodulation according to the input signal and produces a pulse-width-modulated output.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A phase-modulated class-D audio amplifier was described in a patent assigned to Peavey Electronics, in which the AC mains are rectified only to drive the primary switching stage, with no secondary-side DC supply rails, and the output is recovered using a low-pass filter.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Class-D amplifiers work by generating a train of rectangular pulses of fixed amplitude but varying width and separation.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] This *modulation* represents the amplitude variations of the analog audio input signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In some implementations, the pulses are synchronized with an incoming digital audio signal, removing the necessity to convert the signal to analog.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The output of the modulator is then used to turn the output transistors on and off alternately.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Since the transistors are either fully on or fully off, they dissipate very little power.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A simple low-pass filter consisting of an inductor and a capacitor provides a path for the low frequencies of the audio signal, leaving the high-frequency pulses behind.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The structure of a class-D power stage is comparable to that of a synchronously rectified buck converter, a type of non-isolated switched-mode power supply (SMPS).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Whereas buck converters usually function as voltage regulators, delivering a constant DC voltage into a variable load, and can only source current, a class-D amplifier delivers a constantly changing voltage into a fixed load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A switching amplifier may use any type of power supply (e.g., a car battery or an internal SMPS), but the defining characteristic is that the amplification process itself operates by switching.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Some class-D amplifiers use more than two output voltage levels to improve efficiency and reduce component size by switching in smaller voltage steps.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] This reduces switching ripple current and allows the use of smaller output inductors.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] One implementation uses flying-capacitor half-bridges to produce three-level waveforms from a single supply rail, or five-level waveforms in bridge-tied-load configurations.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] This has been demonstrated in monolithic audio power amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] An alternative approach generates multiple output voltage levels using stacked or series-connected switching devices, without flying capacitors, in which voltage stress is shared across devices while the output stage generates multilevel PWM.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The theoretical power efficiency of class-D amplifiers using ideal switches is 100%.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] That is to say, all of the power supplied to it is delivered to the load, and none is turned to heat.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] This is because an ideal switch in its *on* state would encounter no resistance and conduct all the current with no voltage drop across it, hence no power would be dissipated as heat.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] And when it is *off*, it would have the full supply voltage across it but no leakage current flowing through it, and again no power would be dissipated.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Real-world power MOSFETs are not ideal switches, but practical efficiencies well over 90% are common for class-D amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] By contrast, linear AB-class amplifiers are always operated with both current flowing through and voltage standing across the power devices.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] An ideal class-B amplifier has a theoretical maximum efficiency of 78%.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Class-A amplifiers (purely linear, with the devices always at least partially *on*) have a theoretical maximum efficiency of 50%, and some designs have efficiencies below 20%.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The 2-level waveform is derived using pulse-width modulation (PWM), pulse-density modulation (sometimes referred to as pulse frequency modulation), sliding mode control (more commonly called *self-oscillating modulation*) or discrete-time forms of modulation such as delta-sigma modulation.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A simple means of creating the PWM signal is to use a high-speed comparator ("**C**" in the block diagram above) that compares a high-frequency triangular wave with the audio input.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] This generates a series of pulses, of which the duty cycle is directly proportional to the instantaneous value of the audio signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The comparator then drives a MOS gate driver, which in turn drives a pair of high-power switching transistors (usually MOSFETs).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] This produces an amplified replica of the comparator's PWM signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The output filter removes the high-frequency switching components of the PWM signal and reconstructs audio information that the speaker can use.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] DSP-based amplifiers that generate a PWM signal directly from a digital audio signal (e.g., SPDIF) either use a counter to time the pulse length or implement a digital equivalent of the triangle-based modulator.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In either case, the time resolution afforded by practical clock frequencies is only a few hundredths of a switching period, which is not enough to ensure low noise.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In effect, the pulse length gets quantized, resulting in quantization distortion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In both cases, negative feedback is applied inside the digital domain, forming a noise shaper which results in lower noise in the audible frequency range.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Two significant design challenges for MOSFET driver circuits in class-D amplifiers are keeping dead times and linear mode operation as short as possible.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] *Dead time* is the period during a switching transition when both output MOSFETs are driven into cut-off mode and both are *off*.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Failures that allow shoot-through or too much linear mode operation result in excessive losses and sometimes catastrophic failure of the MOSFETs.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] With fixed-frequency PWM modulation, as the (peak) output voltage approaches either of the supply rails, the pulse width can get so narrow as to challenge the ability of the driver circuit and the MOSFET to respond.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] These pulses can be as short as a few nanoseconds and can result in shoot-through and heating due to linear mode operation.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Other modulation techniques, such as pulse-density modulation, can achieve higher peak output voltages, as well as greater efficiency compared to fixed-frequency PWM.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Class-D amplifiers place an additional requirement on their power supply, namely that it be able to sink energy returning from the load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Reactive (capacitive or inductive) loads store energy during part of a cycle and release some of this energy back later.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Linear amplifiers will dissipate this energy; class-D amplifiers return it to the power supply, which should somehow be able to store it.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] In addition, half-bridge class-D amplifiers transfer energy from one supply rail (e.g., the positive rail) to the other (e.g., the negative) depending on the sign of the output current.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] This happens with both resistive and reactive loads.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The supply should either have enough capacitive storage on both rails, or be able to transfer this energy to the other rail.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The active devices in a class-D amplifier need only act as controllable switches and need not have a particularly linear response to the control input.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The actual output of the amplifier is not just dependent on the content of the modulated PWM signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A number of sources may introduce errors.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Any variation in power supply voltage directly amplitude-modulates the output voltage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Dead time errors make the output impedance non-linear.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The output filter has a strongly load-dependent frequency response.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] An effective way to combat errors, regardless of their source, is negative feedback.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] A feedback loop including the output stage can be made using a simple integrator.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] To include the output filter, a PID controller is used, sometimes with additional integrating terms.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The need to feed the actual output signal back into the modulator makes the direct generation of PWM from a SPDIF source unattractive.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Mitigating the same issues in an amplifier without feedback requires addressing each separately at the source.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Power supply modulation can be partially canceled by measuring the supply voltage to adjust signal gain as part of PWM conversion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Distortion can be reduced by switching faster.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The output impedance cannot be controlled other than through feedback.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] The major advantage of a class-D amplifier is that it can be much more efficient than a linear amplifier, dissipating less power as heat in the active devices.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] This is especially compelling in compact portable, battery-powered devices.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/class-d-amplifier] Also, given that large heat sinks are not required, class-D amplifiers are much lighter weight than class-A, -B, or -AB amplifiers, an important consideration with portable sound reinforcement system equipment and bass amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The design of the distributed amplifiers was first formulated by William S.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] In that year Percival proposed a design by which the transconductances of individual vacuum tubes could be added linearly without lumping their element capacitances at the input and output, thus arriving at a circuit that achieved a gain-bandwidth product greater than that of an individual tube.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Percival's design did not gain widespread awareness however, until a publication on the subject was authored by Ginzton, Hewlett, Jasberg, and Noe in 1948.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] It is to this later paper that the term *distributed amplifier* can actually be traced.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Traditionally, DA design architectures were realized using vacuum tube technology.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] More recently, III-V semiconductor technologies, such as GaAs and InP have been used.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] These have superior performance resulting from higher bandgaps (higher electron mobility), higher saturated electron velocity, higher breakdown voltages and higher-resistivity substrates.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The latter contributes much to the availability of higher quality-factor (Q-factor or simply Q) integrated passive devices in the III-V semiconductor technologies.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] To meet the marketplace demands on cost, size, and power consumption of monolithic microwave integrated circuits (MMICs), research continues in the development of mainstream digital bulk-CMOS processes for such purposes.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The continuous scaling of feature sizes in current IC technologies has enabled microwave and mm-wave CMOS circuits to directly benefit from the resulting increased unity-gain frequencies of the scaled technology.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] This device scaling, along with the advanced process control available in today's technologies, has recently made it possible to reach a transition frequency (ft) of 170 GHz and a maximum oscillation frequency (fmax) of 240 GHz in a 90 nm CMOS process.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The operation of the DA can perhaps be most easily understood when explained in terms of the traveling-wave tube amplifier (TWTA).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The DA consists of a pair of transmission lines with characteristic impedances of Z0 independently connecting the inputs and outputs of several active devices.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] An RF signal is thus supplied to the section of transmission line connected to the input of the first device.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] As the input signal propagates down the input line, the individual devices respond to the forward traveling input step by inducing an amplified complementary forward traveling wave on the output line.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] This assumes the delays of the input and output lines are made equal through selection of propagation constants and lengths of the two lines and as such the output signals from each individual device sum in phase.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Terminating resistors Zg and Zd are placed to minimize destructive reflections.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The transconductive gain of each device is gm and the output impedance seen by each transistor is half the characteristic impedance of the transmission line.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Neglecting losses, the gain demonstrates a linear dependence on the number of devices (stages).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Unlike the multiplicative nature of a cascade of conventional amplifiers, the DA demonstrates an additive quality.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] It is this synergistic property of the DA architecture that makes it possible for it to provide gain at frequencies beyond that of the unity-gain frequency of the individual stages.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] In practice, the number of stages is limited by the diminishing input signal resulting from attenuation on the input line.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Means of determining the optimal number of stages are discussed below.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Bandwidth is typically limited by impedance mismatches brought about by frequency dependent device parasitics.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The DA architecture introduces delay in order to achieve its broadband gain characteristics.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] This delay is a desired feature in the design of another distributive system called the distributed oscillator.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Delay lines are made of lumped elements of L and C.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The parasitic L and the C from the transistors are used for this and usually some L is added to raise the line impedance.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Because of the Miller effect in the common source amplifier the input and the output transmission line are coupled.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] For example, for voltage inverting and current amplifying the input and the output form a shielded balanced line.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The current is increasing in the output transmission line with every subsequent transistor, and therefore less and less L is added to keep the voltage constant and more and more extra C is added to keep the velocity constant.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] This C can come from parasitics of a second stage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] These delay lines do not have a flat dispersion near their cut off, so it is important to use the same L-C periodicity in the input and the output.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] If inserting transmission lines, input and output will disperse away from each other.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] For a distributed amplifier the input is fed in series into the amplifiers and parallel out of them.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] To avoid losses in the input, no input signal is allowed to leak through.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] This is avoided by using a balanced input and output also known as push–pull amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Then all signals which leak through the parasitic capacitances cancel.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The output is combined in a delay line with decreasing impedance.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] For narrow band operation other methods of phase-matching are possible, which avoid feeding the signal through multiple coils and capacitors.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] This may be useful for power-amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The single amplifiers can be of any class.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] There may be some synergy between distributed class E/F amplifiers and some phase-matching methods.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Only the fundamental frequency is used in the end, so this is the only frequency, which travels through the delay line version.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Because of the Miller effect a common source transistor acts as a capacitor (non inverting) at high frequencies and has an inverting transconductance at low frequencies.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The channel of the transistor has three dimensions.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] One dimension, the width, is chosen depending on the current needed.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The trouble is for a single transistor parasitic capacitance and gain both scale linearly with the width.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] For the distributed amplifier the capacitance – that is the width – of the single transistor is chosen based on the highest frequency and the width needed for the current is split across all transistors.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Note that those termination resistors are usually not used in CMOS, but the losses due to these are small in typical applications.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] In solid state power amplifiers often multiple discrete transistors are used for power reasons anyway.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] If all transistors are driven in a synchronized fashion a very high gate drive power is needed.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] For frequencies at which small and efficient coils are available distributed amplifiers are more efficient.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Voltage can be amplified by a common gate transistor, which shows no miller effect and no unit gain frequency cut off.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] Adding this yields the cascode configuration.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/distributed-amplifier] The common gate configuration is incompatible with CMOS; it adds a resistor, that means loss, and is more suited for broadband than for high efficiency applications.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] The **Doherty amplifier** is a high-efficiency linear radio-frequency power amplifier originally developed for high-power amplitude-modulated broadcasting.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] Doherty of Bell Telephone Laboratories in 1936 as a means of maintaining high efficiency over the modulation cycle, particularly in transmitters operating at tens to hundreds of kilowatts, where power consumption and operating cost were significant concerns.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] In the classical Doherty configuration, one amplifier tube (carrier) supplies the required output power under unmodulated carrier conditions, while a second tube (peaking) conducts only during positive modulation peaks.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] Through a coupling network, the load impedance presented to the carrier amplifier is dynamically reduced as the peaking amplifier contributes power.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] This allows both tubes to operate at high efficiency throughout the modulation cycle and to share the power required for positive modulation peaks.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] The coupling network functions as a quarter-wave impedance inverter, and the carrier and peaking amplifiers are driven with radio-frequency signals that are ninety degrees out of phase.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] Early Western Electric Doherty systems used a modulated driver transmitter, typically 5 kW in 50 kW broadcast installations, with the Doherty amplifier providing the final power stage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] After its introduction in 1936, the Doherty amplifier progressed from a laboratory demonstration into commercial broadcast equipment.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] Western Electric developed and marketed AM broadcast transmitters using the Doherty architecture, documenting their installation and use in contemporary promotional literature.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] Later historical reviews indicate that some broadcast stations operating these transmitters reported reductions in operating costs, particularly in electrical power consumption.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] A retrospective article in ''Radio World'' describes broadcaster claims of lower utility expenses and reduced heat dissipation attributed to higher average efficiency, especially under typical program conditions where full modulation peaks occurred infrequently.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] These reports reflect how the Doherty amplifier was perceived by broadcasters in practical service rather than in controlled performance tests.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] The technical influence of the Doherty amplifier extended well beyond its initial broadcast applications.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] Doherty applied for the original patent in 1936, and it was issued in 1940 as U.S.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] This patent was cited extensively in later work, including at least 154 subsequent patents.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] Subsequent patents explored variations on the original concept while retaining the principle of dynamic load sharing.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] These included alternative circuits and device operating modes.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] A later patent by Weldon described a configuration in which one stage operated as a cathode follower, illustrating refinement of the original architecture rather than its replacement.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] Modern analyses have revisited classical high-efficiency RF power amplifier techniques, such as those of Doherty, and have shown their continued relevance.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/doherty-amplifier] A detailed analysis is given in the 2002 literature.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In electronics, **power amplifier classes** are letter symbols applied to different power amplifier types.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The class gives a broad indication of an amplifier's efficiency, linearity and other characteristics.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Broadly, as you go through the alphabet, the amplifiers become more efficient but less linear, and the reduced linearity is dealt with through other means.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The first classes, A, AB, B, and C, are related to the time period that the active amplifier device is passing current, expressed as a fraction of the period of a signal waveform applied to the input.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This metric is known as conduction angle ( $\theta$ ).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] A class-A amplifier is conducting through the entire period of the signal ( $\theta =360$ °); class-B only for one-half the input period ( $\theta =180$ °), class-C for much less than half the input period ( $\theta <<180$ °).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-D and E amplifiers operate their output device in a switching manner; the fraction of the time that the device is conducting may be adjusted so a pulse-width modulation output (or other frequency based modulation) can be obtained from the stage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Additional letter classes are defined for special-purpose amplifiers, with additional active elements, power supply improvements, or output tuning; sometimes a new letter symbol is also used by a manufacturer to promote its proprietary design.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] By December 2010, classes AB and D dominated nearly all of the audio amplifier market with the former being favored in portable music players, home audio and cell phone owing to lower cost of class-AB chips.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In the illustrations below, a bipolar junction transistor is shown as the amplifying device.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] However, the same attributes are found with MOSFETs or vacuum tubes.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In a class-A amplifier, 100% of the input signal is used (conduction angle $\theta =360$ °).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The active element remains continuously conducting.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Their output stage transistors are biased for class-A operation, leading to a continual drain current.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This means class-A amplifiers have poor efficiency and heat is generated in the transistor, typically requiring thermal management.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Subclasses A1 and A2 are sometimes used to refer to vacuum-tube class-A amplifiers that drive the grid slightly negative or positive respectively on signal peaks for slightly more power than normal class-A.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This, however, incurs higher signal distortion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-A power amplifier designs have largely been superseded by more efficient designs, though their simplicity makes them popular with some hobbyists.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] There is a market for expensive high fidelity class-A amps considered a "cult item" among audiophiles mainly for their absence of crossover distortion and reduced odd-harmonic and high-order harmonic distortion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-A power amplifiers are also used in some "boutique" guitar amplifiers due to their unique tonal quality and for reproducing vintage tones.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Transistors are much less expensive than tubes so more elaborate designs that use more parts are still less expensive to manufacture than tube designs.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] A classic application for a pair of class-A devices is the long-tailed pair, which is exceptionally linear, and forms the basis of many more complex circuits, including many audio amplifiers and almost all op-amps.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-A amplifiers may be used in output stages of op-amps (although the accuracy of the bias in low cost op-amps such as the "741" may result in class-A or class-AB or class-B performance, varying from device to device or with temperature).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] They are sometimes used as medium-power, low-efficiency, and high-cost audio power amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The power consumption is unrelated to the output power.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] At idle (no input), the power consumption is essentially the same as at high output volume.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The result is low efficiency and high heat dissipation.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In a class-B amplifier, the active device conducts for 180 degrees of the cycle (conduction angle θ = 180°).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Because only half the waveform is amplified, significant harmonic distortion is directly present in the output signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Therefore, class-B amplifiers are generally operated with tuned loading - where harmonics are shorted to ground by a series of resonators.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Another method of reducing distortion, especially at audio frequencies, is to use two transistor devices in a push-pull configuration.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Each conducts for one half (180°) of the signal cycle, and the device currents are combined so that the load current is continuous.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] At radio frequency, if the coupling to the load is via a tuned circuit, a single device operating in class B can be used because the stored energy in the tuned circuit supplies the "missing" half of the waveform.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Devices operating in class-B are used in linear amplifiers, so called because the radio frequency output power is proportional to the square of the input excitation voltage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is more easily understood if stated as "output voltage is proportional to input voltage, thus output power is proportional to input power." This characteristic prevents distortion of amplitude-modulated or frequency-modulated signals passing through the amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Such amplifiers have an efficiency around 60%.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] When Class-B amplifiers amplify the signal with two active devices, each operates over one half of the cycle.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Efficiency is much improved over class-A amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-B amplifiers are also favoured in battery-operated devices, such as transistor radios.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-B has a maximum theoretical efficiency of π/4 (≈ 78.5%).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] A practical circuit using class-B elements is the push–pull stage, such as the very simplified complementary pair arrangement shown at right.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Complementary devices are each used for amplifying the opposite halves of the input signal, which is then recombined at the output.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This arrangement gives good efficiency, but usually suffers from the drawback that there is a small mismatch in the cross-over region – at the "joins" between the two halves of the signal, as one output device has to take over supplying power exactly as the other finishes.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] An improvement is to bias the devices so they are not completely off when they are not in use.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This approach is called *class AB* operation.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In a class-AB amplifier, the conduction angle is intermediate between class-A and -B (conduction angle θ > 180°); each one of the two active elements conducts more than half of the time.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The crossover distortion can be reduced further by using negative feedback.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In class-AB operation, each device operates the same way as in class-B over half the waveform, but also conducts a small amount on the other half.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] As a result, the region where both devices simultaneously are nearly off (the "dead zone") is reduced.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The result is that when the waveforms from the two devices are combined, the crossover is greatly minimised or eliminated altogether.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The exact choice of quiescent current (the standing current through both devices when there is no signal) makes a large difference to the level of distortion (and to the risk of thermal runaway, which may damage the devices).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Often, bias voltage applied to set this quiescent current must be adjusted with the temperature of the output transistors.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-AB sacrifices some efficiency over class-B in favor of linearity, thus is less efficient (below 78.5% for full-amplitude sine waves in transistor amplifiers, typically; much less is common in class-AB vacuum-tube amplifiers).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] It is typically much more efficient than class-A.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] A vacuum tube amplifier design will sometimes have an additional suffix number for the class, for example, class-B1.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] A suffix 1 indicates that grid current does not flow during any part of the input waveform, where a suffix 2 indicates grid current flows for part of the input waveform.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This distinction affects the design of the driver stages for the amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Suffix numbers are not used for semiconductor amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In a class-C amplifier, less than 50% of the input signal is used (conduction angle θ < 180°).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Distortion is high and practical use requires a tuned circuit as load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Efficiency can reach 80% in radio-frequency applications.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The usual application for class-C amplifiers is in RF transmitters operating at a single fixed carrier frequency, where the distortion is controlled by a tuned load on the amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The input signal is used to switch the active device, causing pulses of current to flow through a tuned circuit forming part of the load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The class-C amplifier has two modes of operation: tuned and untuned.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The diagram shows a waveform from a simple class-C circuit without the tuned load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is called untuned operation, and the analysis of the waveforms shows the massive distortion that appears in the signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] When the proper load (e.g., an inductive-capacitive filter plus a load resistor) is used, two things happen.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The first is that the output's bias level is clamped with the average output voltage equal to the supply voltage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is why tuned operation is sometimes called a *clamper*.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This restores the waveform to its proper shape, despite the amplifier having only a one-polarity supply.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is directly related to the second phenomenon: the waveform on the center frequency becomes less distorted.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The residual distortion is dependent upon the bandwidth of the tuned load, with the center frequency seeing very little distortion, but greater attenuation the farther from the tuned frequency that the signal gets.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The tuned circuit resonates at one frequency, the fixed carrier frequency, and so the unwanted frequencies are suppressed, and the wanted full signal (sine wave) is extracted by the tuned load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The signal bandwidth of the amplifier is limited by the Q-factor of the tuned circuit but this is not a serious limitation.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Any residual harmonics can be removed using a further filter.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In practical class-C amplifiers a tuned load is invariably used.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In one common arrangement the resistor shown in the circuit above is replaced with a parallel-tuned circuit consisting of an inductor and capacitor in parallel, whose components are chosen to resonate at the frequency of the input signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Power can be coupled to a load by transformer action with a secondary coil wound on the inductor.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The average voltage at the collector is then equal to the supply voltage, and the signal voltage appearing across the tuned circuit varies from near zero to near twice the supply voltage during the RF cycle.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The input circuit is biased so that the active element (e.g., transistor) conducts for only a fraction of the RF cycle, usually one-third (120 degrees) or less.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The active element conducts only while the collector voltage is passing through its minimum.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] By this means, power dissipation in the active device is minimised, and efficiency increased.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Ideally, the active element would pass only an instantaneous current pulse while the voltage across it is zero: it then dissipates no power and 100% efficiency is achieved.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] However practical devices have a limit to the peak current they can pass, and the pulse must therefore be widened, to around 120 degrees, to obtain a reasonable amount of power, and the efficiency is then 60–70%.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-D amplifiers use some form of pulse-width modulation to control the output devices.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The conduction angle of each device is no longer related directly to the input signal but instead varies in pulse width.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In the class-D amplifier the active devices (transistors) function as electronic switches instead of linear gain devices; they are either on or off.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The analog signal is converted to a stream of pulses that represents the signal by pulse-width modulation, pulse-density modulation, delta-sigma modulation or a related modulation technique before being applied to the amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The time average power value of the pulses is directly proportional to the analog signal, so after amplification the signal can be converted back to an analog signal by a passive low-pass filter.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The purpose of the output filter is to smooth the pulse stream to an analog signal, removing the high-frequency spectral components of the pulses.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The frequency of the output pulses is typically ten or more times the highest frequency in the input signal to amplify, so that the filter can adequately reduce the unwanted harmonics and accurately reproduce the input.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The main advantage of a class-D amplifier is power efficiency.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Efficiency over 90% is achievable with MOSFETs and >80% is fairly common.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Because the output pulses have a fixed amplitude, the switching elements (usually MOSFETs, but vacuum tubes and bipolar transistors have also been used) are switched completely on or completely off, rather than operating in linear mode.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] A MOSFET generally operates with the lowest on-state resistance when fully on and thus (excluding when fully off) has the lowest power dissipation when in that condition.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Compared to an equivalent class-AB device, a class-D amplifier's lower losses permit the use of smaller heat sinks for the MOSFETs while also reducing the amount of input power required, allowing for a lower-capacity power supply design.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Therefore, class-D amplifiers are typically smaller than an equivalent class-AB amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Another advantage of the class-D amplifier is that it can operate from a digital signal source without requiring a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) to convert the signal to analog form first.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] A class-D amplifier with moderate output power can be constructed using regular CMOS logic process, making it suitable for integration with other types of digital circuitry.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Thus it is commonly found in System-on-Chips with integrated audio when the amplifier shares a die with the main processor or DSP.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] While class-D amplifiers are widely used to control motors, they are also used as power amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Though if the signal is not already in a pulse modulated format prior to amplification, it must first be converted, which may require additional circuitry.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Switching power supplies have even been modified into crude class-D amplifiers (though typically these only reproduce low-frequencies with acceptable accuracy).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] High-quality class-D audio power amplifiers are readily available on the market.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Dynamic range of 118 dB in a high-end consumer product was seen in the year 2009.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Most, however, remain closer to 100 dB dynamic range at this time [2022] due to practical cost considerations.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] These designs have been said to rival traditional class A and AB amplifiers in terms of quality.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] An early use of class-D amplifiers was high-power subwoofer amplifiers in cars.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Because subwoofers are generally limited to a bandwidth of no higher than 150 Hz, switching speed for the amplifier does not have to be as high as for a full range amplifier, allowing simpler designs.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-D amplifiers for driving subwoofers are relatively inexpensive in comparison to class-AB amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The letter *D* used to designate this amplifier class is simply the next letter after *C* and, although occasionally used as such, does not stand for *digital*.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-D and class-E amplifiers are sometimes mistakenly described as "digital" because the output waveform superficially resembles a pulse-train of digital symbols, but a class-D amplifier merely converts an input waveform into a continuously pulse-width modulated analog signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Other amplifier classes are mainly variations of the previous classes.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] For example, class-G and class-H amplifiers are marked by variation of the supply rails (in discrete steps or in a continuous fashion, respectively) following the input signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Wasted heat on the output devices can be reduced as excess voltage is kept to a minimum.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The amplifier that is fed with these rails itself can be of any class.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] These kinds of amplifiers are more complex, and are mainly used for specialized applications, such as very high-power units.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Also, class-E and class-F amplifiers are commonly described in literature for radio-frequency applications where efficiency of the traditional classes is important, yet several aspects deviate substantially from their ideal values.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] These classes use harmonic tuning of their output networks to achieve higher efficiency and can be considered a subset of class C due to their conduction-angle characteristics.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The class-E amplifier is a highly efficient tuned switching power amplifier used at radio frequencies.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] It uses a single-pole switching element and a tuned reactive network between the switch and the load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The circuit obtains high efficiency by only operating the switching element at points of zero current (on to off switching) or zero voltage (off to on switching) which minimizes power lost in the switch, even when the switching time of the devices is long compared to the frequency of operation.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The class-E amplifier is frequently cited to have been first reported in 1975 by Alan and Nathan Sokal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] However, a full description of class-E operation may be found in the 1964 doctoral thesis of Gerald D.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Interestingly, analytical design equations only recently became known.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In push–pull amplifiers and in CMOS, the even harmonics of both transistors just cancel.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Experiment shows that a square wave can be generated by those amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Theoretically square waves consist of odd harmonics only.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In a class-D amplifier, the output filter blocks all harmonics; i.e., the harmonics see an open load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] So even small currents in the harmonics suffice to generate a voltage square wave.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The current is in phase with the voltage applied to the filter, but the voltage across the transistors is out of phase.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Therefore, there is a minimal overlap between current through the transistors and voltage across the transistors.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The sharper the edges, the lower the overlap.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] While in class-D, transistors and the load exist as two separate modules, class-F admits imperfections like the parasitics of the transistor and tries to optimise the global system to have a high impedance at the harmonics.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Of course there must be a finite voltage across the transistor to push the current across the on-state resistance.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Because the combined current through both transistors is mostly in the first harmonic, it looks like a sine.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] That means that in the middle of the square the maximum of current has to flow, so it may make sense to have a dip in the square or in other words to allow some overswing of the voltage square wave.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] A class-F load network by definition has to transmit below a cutoff frequency and reflect above.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Any frequency lying below the cutoff and having its second harmonic above the cutoff can be amplified, that is an octave bandwidth.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] On the other hand, an inductive-capacitive series circuit with a large inductance and a tunable capacitance may be simpler to implement.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] By reducing the duty cycle below 0.5, the output amplitude can be modulated.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The voltage square waveform degrades, but any overheating is compensated by the lower overall power flowing.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Any load mismatch behind the filter can only act on the first harmonic current waveform, clearly only a purely resistive load makes sense, then the lower the resistance, the higher the current.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-F can be driven by sine or by a square wave, for a sine the input can be tuned by an inductor to increase gain.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] If class-F is implemented with a single transistor, the filter is complicated to short the even harmonics.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] All previous designs use sharp edges to minimise the overlap.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] There are a variety of amplifier designs that enhance class-AB output stages with more efficient techniques to achieve greater efficiency with low distortion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] These designs are common in large audio amplifiers since the heatsinks and power transformers would be prohibitively large (and costly) without the efficiency increases.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The terms "class-G" and "class-H" are used interchangeably to refer to different designs, varying in definition from one manufacturer or paper to another.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-G amplifiers (which use "rail switching" to decrease power consumption and increase efficiency) are more efficient than class-AB amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] These amplifiers provide several power rails at different voltages and switch between them as the signal output approaches each level.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Thus, the amplifier increases efficiency by reducing the wasted power at the output transistors.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-G amplifiers are more efficient than class AB but less efficient when compared to class-D.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] However, they do not have the electromagnetic interference effects of class D.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] Class-H amplifiers create an infinitely variable (analog) supply rail.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] They are sometimes referred to as rail trackers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is done by modulating the supply rails so that the rails are only a few volts larger than the output signal "tracking" it at any given time.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The output stage operates at its maximum efficiency all the time.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is due to the circuit ability to keep the rail transistors (T2 and T4) in cutoff until a music voltage peak is of a sufficient magnitude to require the additional voltage from the + and - 80 V supplies.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The class H amplifier can actually be thought of as two amplifiers in series.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In the schematic example shown by the figure, +/- 40 V rail amplifiers can produce about 100 watts continuous into an 8-ohm load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] If the output signal is operating below 40 volts, the amplifier only has the losses associated with a 100 W amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is because the class-H upper devices T2 and T4 are only used when the music signal is between 100 and 400 watts output.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The key to understanding this efficiency without churning the actual numbers is that we have a 400-watt-capable amplifier but with the efficiency of a 100-watt amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is because the waveforms of music contain long periods under 100 watts and contain only brief bursts of up to 400 watts – in other words, the losses at 400 watts are for brief time periods.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] If this example were drawn as a class AB with just the 80 V supplies in place of the 40 V supplies, the T1 and T3 transistors would need to be in conduction throughout the 0 V to 80 V signal with the corresponding losses all through the wave period - not just the brief high energy bursts.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] To achieve this rail tracking control, T2 and T4 act as current amplifiers, each in series with its low voltage counterpart T1 and T3.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The purpose of T2 and T3 is to allow back-biasing diode D2 when the amplifier output is at a positive peak (above 39.3 V) and back biasing D4 when the output is at negative peak less than -39.3 V.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] During the musical peaks from 100 to 400 watts, the +/-40 V rails source no current as all the current comes from the +/-80 V rails.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This figure is too simplistic, however, as it will not actually control the T2 and T4 transistors at all.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] This is because the D1 and D3 diodes which are intended to provide a path for the output voltage back into the upper devices are always reverse biased.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] In place of these diodes, a voltage amplifier with gain which uses vout as its input would be needed in an actual design.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] There is another reason for this gain requirement between vout and T2 base in an actual class-H design and that is to assure that the signal applied to the T2 is always "ahead" of the Vout signal so it can never "catch up" with the rail tracker.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier-classes] The rail tracker amplifier might have a 50 V/μs slew rate while the class-AB amplifier might have only a 30 V/μs slew rate in order to guarantee this.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] An **audio power amplifier** (or **power amp**) amplifies low-power electronic audio signals, such as the signal from a radio receiver or an electric guitar pickup, to a level that is high enough for driving loudspeakers or headphones.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Audio power amplifiers are found in all manner of sound systems, including sound reinforcement, public address, home audio systems and musical instrument amplifiers like guitar amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] It is the final electronic stage in a typical audio playback chain before the signal is sent to the loudspeakers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The preceding stages in such a chain are low-power audio amplifiers, which perform tasks like pre-amplification of the signal, equalization, mixing different input signals.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The inputs can also be any number of audio sources like record players, CD players, digital audio players and cassette players.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Most audio power amplifiers require these low-level inputs, which are line level.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The audio amplifier was invented around 1912 by Lee de Forest.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] This was made possible by his invention of the first practical amplifying electrical component, the triode vacuum tube (or "valve" in British English) in 1907.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The triode was a three-terminal device with a control grid that can modulate the flow of electrons from the filament to the plate.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The triode vacuum amplifier was used to make the first AM radio.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Early audio power amplifiers were based on vacuum tubes and some of these achieved notably high audio quality (e.g., the Williamson amplifier of 1947–9).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Audio power amplifiers based on transistors became practical with the wide availability of inexpensive transistors in the late 1960s.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Since the 1970s, most modern audio amplifiers are based on solid-state transistors, especially the bipolar junction transistor (BJT) and the metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Transistor-based amplifiers are lighter in weight, more reliable and require less maintenance than tube amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960. was adapted into a power MOSFET for audio by Jun-ichi Nishizawa at Tohoku University in 1974.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Power MOSFETs were soon manufactured by Yamaha for their hi-fi audio amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] JVC, Pioneer Corporation, Sony and Toshiba also began manufacturing amplifiers with power MOSFETs in 1974.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] In 1977, Hitachi introduced the LDMOS (lateral diffused MOS), a type of power MOSFET.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Hitachi was the only LDMOS manufacturer between 1977 and 1983, during which time LDMOS was used in audio power amplifiers from manufacturers such as HH Electronics (V-series) and Ashly Audio, and were used for music and public address systems.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Class-D amplifiers became successful in the mid-1980s when low-cost, fast-switching MOSFETs were made available.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Many transistor amps use MOSFET devices in their power sections, because their distortion curve is more tube-like.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Key design parameters for audio power amplifiers are frequency response, gain, noise, and distortion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] These are interdependent; increasing gain often leads to undesirable increases in noise and distortion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] While negative feedback actually reduces the gain, it also reduces distortion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Most audio amplifiers are linear amplifiers operating in class AB.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Until the 1970s, most amplifiers used vacuum tubes.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] During the 1970s, tube amps were increasingly replaced with transistor-based amplifiers, which were lighter in weight, more reliable, and lower maintenance.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The class-D amplifier, which is much more efficient than class-AB amplifiers, is now widely used in consumer electronics audio products, bass amplifiers and sound reinforcement system gear, as class-D amplifiers are much lighter in weight and produce much less heat, but may introduce some noise.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Since modern digital devices, including CD and DVD players, radio receivers and tape decks already provide a "flat" signal at line level, the preamp is not needed other than as a volume control and source selector.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] One alternative to a separate preamp is to simply use passive volume and switching controls, sometimes integrated into a power amplifier to form an integrated amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The final stage of amplification, after preamplifiers, is the output stage, where the highest demands are placed on the transistors or tubes.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] For this reason, the design choices made around the output device (for single-ended output stages, such as in single-ended triode amplifiers) or devices (for push-pull output stages), such as the class of operation of the output devices is often taken as the description of the whole power amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] For example, a class-B amplifier will probably have just the high power output devices operating cut off for half of each cycle, while the other devices (such as differential amplifier, voltage amplifier and possibly even driver transistors) operate in class A.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] In a transformerless output stage, the devices are essentially in series with the power supply and output load (such as a loudspeaker), possibly via some large capacitor and/or small resistances.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] For some years following the introduction of solid-state amplifiers, their *perceived* sound did not have the excellent audio quality of the best valve audio amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] This led audiophiles to believe that tube sound had an intrinsic quality due to the vacuum tube technology itself.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] In 1970, Matti Otala published a paper on transient distortion.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Transient distortion later became known as transient intermodulation distortion (TIM).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Two years later, in a 1972 paper, Matti Otala reported that TIM was found to occur during very rapid increases in amplifier output voltage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Papers also later revealed that TIM distortion was triggered not just by transients, but also by steady state sine tone measurements.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Further publications by Otala and other authors found the solution for TIM distortion, including increasing slew rate, decreasing preamp frequency bandwidth, and the insertion of a lag compensation circuit in the input stage of the amplifier in a way that makes the input stage more linear.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The next step in advanced design was the Baxandall Theorem, created by Peter Baxandall in England.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] This theorem introduced the concept of comparing the ratio between the input distortion and the output distortion of an amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] This new idea helped audio design engineers to better evaluate the distortion processes within an amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] By applying negative feedback, the Baxandall Effect can come into play, where, as the level of negative feedback is increased over a limited range, the 2nd harmonic distortion product is reduced as expected, but at the same time, the higher-order harmonic distortion products are increased instead.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] This has led to the myth that high levels of negative feedback are bad.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] However, as the level of negative feedback is increased beyond approximately 20 dB, all distortion products are further reduced, demonstrating that such higher levels of negative feedback have no downsides.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Important applications include public address systems, theatrical and concert sound reinforcement systems, and domestic systems such as a stereo or home-theatre system.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Instrument amplifiers including guitar amplifiers and electric keyboard amplifiers also use audio power amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] In some cases, the power amplifier for an instrument amplifier is integrated into a single amplifier "head" which contains a preamplifier, tone controls, and electronic effects.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] These components may be mounted in a wooden speaker cabinet to create a "combo amplifier".
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Musicians with unique performance needs and/or a need for very powerful amplification may create a custom setup with separate rackmount preamplifiers, equalizers, and a power amplifier mounted in a 19" road case.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Power amplifiers are available in standalone units, which are used by hi-fi audio enthusiasts and designers of public address systems (PA systems) and sound reinforcement systems.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] A hi-fi user of power amplifiers may have a stereo power amplifier to drive left and right speakers and a single-channel (mono) power amplifier to drive a subwoofer.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] The number of power amplifiers used in a sound reinforcement setting depends on the size of the venue.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] A small coffeehouse may have a single power amp driving two PA speakers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] A nightclub may have several power amps for the main speakers, one or more power amps for the monitor speakers (pointing towards the band) and an additional power amp for the subwoofer.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] A stadium concert may have a large number of power amps mounted in racks.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/power-amplifier] Most consumer electronics sound products, such as TVs, boom boxes, home cinema sound systems, Casio and Yamaha electronic keyboards, "combo" guitar amps and car stereos have power amplifiers integrated inside the chassis of the main product.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] A **radio-frequency power amplifier** (**RF power amplifier**) is a type of electronic amplifier that converts a low-power radio-frequency (RF) signal into a higher-power signal.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Typically, RF power amplifiers are used in the final stage of a radio transmitter, their output driving the antenna.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Design goals often include gain, power output, bandwidth, power efficiency, linearity (low signal compression at rated output), input and output impedance matching, and heat dissipation.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] The operation of RF amplifier circuits is classified based on the proportion of the cycle of the sinusoidal radio signal the amplifier (transistor or vacuum tube) where current is conducting.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Class-A, class-AB and class-B are considered the linear amplifier classes in which the active device is used as a controlled current source, while class-C is a nonlinear class in which the active device is used as a switch.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] The bias at the input of the active device determines the class of the amplifier.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] A common trade-off in power amplifier design is the trade-off between efficiency and linearity.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] The previously named classes become more efficient, but less linear, in the order they are listed.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Operating the active device as a switch results in higher efficiency, theoretically up to 100%, but lower linearity.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Among the switch-mode classes are class-D, class-E and class-F.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] The class-D amplifier is not often used in RF applications because the finite switching speed of the active devices and possible charge storage in saturation could lead to a large I-V product, which deteriorates efficiency.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Modern RF power amplifiers use solid-state devices, predominantly MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] The earliest MOSFET-based RF amplifiers date back to the mid-1960s.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Bipolar junction transistors were also commonly used in the past, up until they were replaced by power MOSFETs, particularly LDMOS transistors, as the standard technology for RF power amplifiers by the 1990s,BJT are still commonly used for high frequency power amplifiers.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Generally speaking, solid-state power amplifiers (SSPA) contain four main components: input, output, amplification stage and power supply.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] MOSFET transistors and other modern solid-state devices have replaced vacuum tubes in most electronic devices, but tubes are still used in some high-power transmitters (see Valve RF amplifier).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Although mechanically robust, transistors are electrically fragile – they are easily damaged by excess voltage or current.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Tubes are mechanically fragile but electrically robust – they can handle remarkably high electrical overloads without appreciable damage.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] The basic applications of the RF power amplifier include driving to another high-power source, driving a transmitting antenna and exciting microwave cavity resonators.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Among these applications, driving transmitter antennas is most well known.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] The transmitter–receivers are used not only for voice and data communication but also for weather sensing (in the form of a radar).
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] RF power amplifiers using LDMOS (laterally diffused MOSFET) are the most widely used power semiconductor devices in wireless telecommunication networks, particularly mobile networks.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] LDMOS-based RF power amplifiers are widely used in digital mobile networks such as 2G, 3G, and 4G and the good cost/performance ratio make them the preferred option for amateur radio.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] Impedance transformations over large bandwidth are difficult to realize, so conventionally, most wideband amplifiers are designed to feed a 50 Ω output load.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] is chosen so that the rated power can be met.
[src:power-amplifier-rf/rf-power-amplifier] The loadline method is often used in RF power amplifier design.
